# CODEOWNERS — L3 surfaces require the owner's independent review.
#
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#  ⚠️  THIS FILE ALONE IS NOT A GATE. Two prerequisites are still MISSING:
#
#   1. Branch protection must set `require_code_owner_reviews = true`
#      (currently FALSE — so these entries are advisory only).
#
#   2. A SECOND account or team that can independently approve must exist.
#      With a single account, the author IS the code owner and cannot
#      self-approve, so enabling (1) today would permanently DEADLOCK every
#      L3 PR rather than gate it.
#
#      → Do (2) first, then (1). Enabling (1) without (2) is a foot-gun.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Why these paths (docs/PRODUCT_STRATEGY.md §7.1): touching auth, authorization,
# customer data, an AI-output sink, a model-release gate, lifecycle write-back, or
# cross-system writes automatically promotes work to L3. Authors may not self-downgrade it.
#
# This file exists because an unattended cadence loop authored a model-release gate
# (#509/#510) and produced a FAKE-GREEN gate: the sanctioned producer could emit a
# PASSING artifact with zero holdout rows and all-zero metrics. §4.7 — "the author of a
# guard must not be the only author or reviewer of the discriminator that claims to prove
# it" — earned its place on the very first L3 attempt. An unattended loop cannot be both
# author and independent critic.

